stylometry: Our group project involved the landscaping company that I work for during the summer.  We examined the four main business activities of the business and the profitability of each activity.  These activities were concrete installation, landscape installation, hardscape (walls and patios), and landscape maintenance.  We included labor costs and any easily predictable fixed costs (like the cost of renting concrete equipment or truck and mower maintenance costs).  We omitted some costs, as they vary greatly from job to job and are too difficult to predict (like the cost of plants for an installation.)  We used @RISK to run simulation models at different levels of demand.  We based our estimates for demand on data from roughly 2 months last summer.  We examined this problem because, as a small landscape firm (only 3 full time employees) resources (especially time) are limited and we wanted to maximize the return on those resources.  We also wanted to know whether it would be a wise decision to hire more employees, and if so, how many employees to hire.  Based on the data from last year and the simulation models we ran, we learned that it is not necessary to hire any additional employees because we are currently able to meet our customers' demands with current staff.  Demand would have to significantly increase to necessitate more employees.  Also, we learned that the lack of consistent demand for concrete installation coupled with the fixed costs associated with pouring concrete made installing concrete a net loss in every simulation we ran.  Therefore, my company should stop pouring concrete (but try telling that to my boss.)
